This is a simplified version of the Git Flow branching strategy. The idea is that every branch has a specific purpose, so you never do all your work directly on main. 

main
     ?
     ??? feature/auth
     ??? feature/dashboard
     ??? feature/resume-builder
     ??? feature/parser
     ??? feature/ai

feature/auth

?

Pull Request

?

main

Since you're the only developer, a dedicated develop branch isn't strictly necessary. GitHub's Pull Requests still let you review changes, run automated checks (if you add them), and keep main clean. As the project grows or if collaborators join, introducing a develop branch becomes more valuable. 

and where will i put the front end and back end folders and branches? 

This is one of the first architectural decisions you'll make. For this project, I recommend using a monorepo, where both the frontend and backend live in the same Git repository. 

Your Git repository would look like this: 

resume-builder/
?
??? frontend/
?   ??? src/
?   ??? public/
?   ??? package.json
?   ??? ...
?
??? backend/
?   ??? app/
?   ??? tests/
?   ??? requirements.txt
?   ??? ...
?
??? docs/
?   ??? roadmap.md
?   ??? sitemap.md
?   ??? api-spec.md
?   ??? ...
?
??? .gitignore
??? README.md
??? LICENSE

Notice there's only one .git folder at the root. 

What I Recommend for This Project 

resume-builder/
?
??? frontend/
??? backend/
??? docs/
??? docker/
??? scripts/
??? README.md
??? docker-compose.yml
??? .gitignore

One repository.
One set of branches.
Branches organized by feature rather than by frontend/backend.
This is how many professional teams organize full-stack applications because it keeps all the code needed for a feature together and makes changes easier to review and understand.
The key thing to understand is that folders and branches are two completely different concepts.
    • Folders organize your files. 
    • Branches organize your project's history.
They don't contain each other. 

Think of it like a video game save file
Imagine your project is a game world.
The folders are the world itself:
resume-builder/
?
??? frontend/
??? backend/
??? docs/
??? ...
The branches are different save files of that world.
Save 1: main
Save 2: feature/auth
Save 3: feature/parser
Save 4: feature/ai
Each save contains the entire world, but in a different state.
Your Repository
On your computer you'll literally have this:
resume-builder/
?
??? frontend/
??? backend/
??? docs/
??? docker/
??? scripts/
??? README.md
??? .git/
Notice the hidden .git folder.
That folder stores all the branch information.
It might look conceptually like this:
resume-builder/
?
??? frontend/
??? backend/
??? docs/
??? .git/
?     ??? main
?     ??? develop
?     ??? feature/auth
?     ??? feature/dashboard
?     ??? feature/parser
?     ??? ...
You normally never touch .git directly.
When you switch branches...
Suppose you're on main.
Your project looks like this:
resume-builder/
frontend/
backend/
docs/
Now run:
git checkout feature/auth
Your folders stay exactly the same.
resume-builder/
frontend/
backend/
docs/
What changes is the contents inside those folders.
